\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Sechelt is the name of a town, a peninsula, an inlet, and a people. The town is a small community sitting on a sandbar, the narrow Sechelt isthmus which separates Sechelt Inlet from the Strait of Georgia. Named after the original First Nations people of the region, the Sh\'edsh\'e1lh, the word Sechelt means "land between two waters."\
Indian legend has it that the creator gods were sent by the Divine Spirit to form the world. They carved out valleys leaving a beach along the inlet at Porpoise Bay. Later, the transformers, a male raven and a female mink, added details by carving trees and forming pools of water. The raven is an integral part of the Sechelt Indian Band's culture and is often seen in their carvings.\
In the 1860's European missionaries first came to Sechelt, resulting in a devastating loss of as many as 90% of the Sh\'edsh\'e1lh population to smallpox.\
